  1275→	/**
  1276→	Opens a device.  This can either open a device chosen arbitrarily from all devices
  1277→	on the system, or open a specific device selected by passing this function the device URI.
  1278→
  1279→	To open any device, simply pass the constant@ref ANY_DEVICE to this function.  If multiple
  1280→	devices are connected to the system, then one of them will be opened.  This procedure is most
  1281→	useful when it is known that exactly one device is (or can be) connected to the system.  In that case,
  1282→	requesting a list of all devices and iterating through it would be a waste of effort.
  1283→
  1284→	If multiple devices are (or may be) connected to a system, then a URI will be required to select
  1285→	a specific device to open.  There are two ways to obtain a URI: from a DeviceConnected event, or
  1286→	by calling @ref OpenNI::enumerateDevices().
  1287→
  1288→	In the case of a DeviceConnected event, the @ref OpenNI::Listener will be provided with a DeviceInfo object
  1289→	as an argument to its @ref OpenNI::Listener::onDeviceConnected "onDeviceConnected()" function.  
  1290→	The DeviceInfo.getUri() function can then be used to obtain the URI.
  1291→
  1292→	If the application is not using event handlers, then it can also call the static function
  1293→	@ref OpenNI::enumerateDevices().  This will return an array of @ref DeviceInfo objects, one for each device
  1294→	currently available to the system.  The application can then iterate through this list and
